# Trivy ignore policy — every entry here is a documented, deliberate risk
# acceptance, NOT a blanket gate disable. The CI Trivy jobs
# (pr-checks.yml fs scan + ci.yml per-image scan) still fail the build on any
# HIGH/CRITICAL finding that is not explicitly listed below (in particular:
# any FIXABLE finding that is not one of the two documented app-dependency
# exceptions will break the build). Review this file whenever it is touched;
# each entry must keep its justification current.
#
# What has been FIXED rather than ignored (so it is NOT in this list):
#   * services/catalog — every Go module CVE was resolved by bumping
#     go.opentelemetry.io/otel* to v1.43.0 and golang.org/x/net / grpc; the
#     catalog image (distroless) scans completely clean.
#   * services/frontend — nginx-unprivileged:alpine image scans clean.
#   * fast-uri path-traversal (api-gateway) — pinned to 3.1.3 via an override.
#   * All FIXABLE Debian OS CVEs in the api-gateway (node:20-slim) and orders
#     (python:3.12-slim) images — cleared by `apt-get -y upgrade` in each
#     Dockerfile's runtime stage.
#   * The npm-CLI-bundled library CVEs (tar, minimatch, glob, cross-spawn,
#     sigstore) in api-gateway — eliminated by removing the unused npm CLI
#     from the runtime image (see services/api-gateway/Dockerfile).

# --- services/api-gateway (our app node_modules) ---
#
# CVE-2026-44902 — @opentelemetry/auto-instrumentations-node /
# @opentelemetry/sdk-node DoS via malformed HTTP request. Fixed only in the
# @opentelemetry/core v2.x line, which requires bumping every
# @opentelemetry/* package in this service in lockstep (v1 -> v2 is a
# breaking API change for the tracing SDK we rely on). That migration needs
# its own regression pass against api-gateway's tracing setup and is out of
# scope for this CI-wiring change. Tracked as follow-up work.
CVE-2026-44902

# CVE-2026-25223 — fastify Content-Type validation bypass. Fixed only in
# fastify v5 (major bump from the v4 this service is pinned to), which is a
# breaking change to route/schema/hook APIs used throughout src/. Requires a
# dedicated migration + regression pass, out of scope here. Tracked as
# follow-up work.
CVE-2026-25223

# --- Debian base-image OS packages with NO upstream fix (Status: affected,
#     FixedVersion: none) in api-gateway (node:20-slim, Debian 12) and orders
#     (python:3.12-slim, Debian 13) ---
#
# These are packages baked into the official Debian base images (perl-base,
# util-linux family, ncurses, gzip, zlib1g, libacl1) that Debian has not yet
# released a security update for — `apt-get upgrade` in the Dockerfiles
# already pulls in everything that IS fixed, so there is nothing to bump to.
# None are reachable from these services' runtime code paths (the containers
# run only `node dist/index.js` / `python -m app.main` as non-root; no shell,
# perl, tar, or util-linux invocation at runtime). Re-run the image scan on
# each base-image bump and drop entries here once Debian ships a fix.
# EXPIRY: re-evaluate on the next base-image bump; remove any that gain a fix.
CVE-2026-53615
CVE-2026-41992
CVE-2026-54369
CVE-2025-69720
CVE-2026-42496
CVE-2026-42497
CVE-2026-48962
CVE-2026-8376
CVE-2026-9538
CVE-2023-45853

# --- terraform (config/misconfig scan) ---
#
# AWS-0132 — S3 bucket (terraform/bootstrap/s3_state.tf, the Terraform state
# bucket) uses SSE-S3 (AES256) rather than a customer-managed KMS key.
# Accepted: the bucket already has versioning, a public-access block, and
# default encryption; it holds Terraform state only. Adding a CMK brings
# extra cost/rotation/IAM-policy surface not justified for this bucket's
# threat model (single AWS account, no cross-account access).
AWS-0132

# AWS-0104 — SonarQube EC2 security group (terraform/stack/sonarqube.tf)
# allows unrestricted egress (0.0.0.0/0). Accepted: the instance needs
# outbound internet access for OS package updates and Docker image pulls
# (SonarQube + Postgres run via docker-compose on it); egress is not the
# ingress attack surface (ingress is already scoped by var.sonar_ingress_cidr
# and SonarQube's own authentication), and restricting egress on a single,
# non-multi-tenant host provides negligible additional security here.
AWS-0104
